04513nam a22006015i 9780887555725DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875557257 a10.1515/97808875557252doi  a(DE-B1597)664568  a(OCoLC)1049913999  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 4aDB200.8b.R375 2018eb 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a305.89/186071090451 aRaska, Jan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCzech Refugees in Cold War Canada :b1945–1989 /cJan Raska. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Immigration and Culture ;v1500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tA Guide to Czech Pronunciation -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tInterwar Farm Labourers, Wartime Enemy Aliens, and Allied Citizens -- tPostwar Relief, Canadian Citizenship, and Ethnic Heritage -- tAftermath of the Communist Takeover: Canada and the 1948ers -- tCommunity Tensions and Ideological Divisions -- tWarsaw Pact Invasion: Canada and the 1968ers -- tOpposing the Communist Regime -- tCreating Ethnocultural Heritage -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the Cold War, more than 36,000 individuals entering Canada claimed Czechoslovakia as their country of citizenship. A defining characteristic of this migration of predominantly political refugees was the prevalence of anti-communist and democratic values. Diplomats, industrialists, politicians, professionals, workers, and students fled to the West in search of freedom, security, and economic opportunity. Jan Raska’s Czech Refugees in Cold War Canada explores how these newcomers joined or formed ethnocultural organizations to help in their attempts to affect developments in Czechoslovakia and Canadian foreign policy towards their homeland. Canadian authorities further legitimized the Czech refugees’ anti-communist agenda and increased their influence in Czechoslovak institutions. In turn, these organizations supported Canada’s Cold War agenda of securing the state from communist infiltration. Ultimately, an adherence to anti-communism, the promotion of Canadian citizenship, and the cultivation of a Czechoslovak ethnocultural heritage accelerated Czech refugees’ socioeconomic and political integration in Cold War Canada. By analyzing oral histories, government files, ethnic newspapers, and community archival records, Raska reveals how Czech refugees secured admission as desirable immigrants and navigated existing social, cultural, and political norms in Cold War Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCzechoslovakszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCzechoslovaks-Canada-History-20th century. 0aCzechszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCzechs-Canada-History-20th century. 0aRefugeeszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aRefugeeszCzechoslovakiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aRefugees-Czechoslovakia-History-20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755572540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887555725423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887555725/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles